33/https://ia800301.us.archive.org/7/items/biennialreportof01west/biennialreportof01west.pdf | archive-date = 1 March 2020 | author-link = West Virginia Department of Education | oclc = 1041611348}}\n* {{cite journal |last= Woodson |first= Carter G. | author-link = Carter G. Woodson | date= July 1921 |title= Notes |url= https://ia801703.us.archive.org/32/items/jstor-2713764/2713764.pdf |journal= [[The Journal of African American History|The Journal of Negro History]] |volume= 6 |issue= 3 |pages=380\u20131 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200301024144/https://ia801703.us.archive.org/32/items/jstor-2713764/2713764.pdf |archive-date= 1 March 2020 |access-date= 1 March 2020 | via = [[Internet Archive]] | publisher = [[Association for the Study of African American Life and History|Association for the Study of Negro Life and History]] | location = Washington, D.C. | ref = harv|doi= 10.1086/JNHv6n3p380 }}\n* {{cite journal |last= Woodson |first= Carter G. | author-link = Carter G. Woodson | date= January 1922 |title= Early Negro Education in West Virginia |url= https://ia601903.us.archive.org/16/items/jstor-2713579/2713579.pdf |journal= [[The Journal of African American History|The Journal of Negro History]] |volume= 7 |issue= 1 |pages=23\u201363 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200229201551/https://ia601903.us.archive.org/16/items/jstor-2713579/2713579.pdf |archive-date= 29 February 2020 |access-date= 29 February 2020 | via = [[Internet Archive]] | publisher = [[Association for the Study of African American Life and History|Association for the Study of Negro Life and History]] | location = Washington, D.C. | ref = harv|doi= 10.2307/2713579 |jstor= 2713579 }}\n* {{cite book |last= Woodson |first= Carter G. | author-link = Carter G. Woodson |year = 2000 | editor-last1 = Conyers | editor-first1 = James L., Jr. | title = Carter G. Woodson: A Historical Reader |publisher = [[Garland Science|Garland Publishing, Inc.]] |location = New York |isbn =  | oclc = 1148191420 |url = https://archive.org/details/cartergwoodsonhi0000wood/ |accessdate = |ref = harv |via = [[Internet Archive]] }}\n{{refend}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Davis, John Warren}}\n[[Category:1888 births]]\n[[Category:1980 deaths]]\n[[Category:20th-century American educators]]\n[[Category:African-American academics]]\n[[Category:African-American publishers (people)]]\n[[Category:African-American university presidents]]\n[[Category:Educators from Georgia (U.S. state)]]\n[[Category:Educators from West Virginia]]\n[[Category:Morehouse College alumni]]\n[[Category:Morehouse College faculty]]\n[[Category:NAACP activists]]\n[[Category:National Education Association people]]\n[[Category:Order of the Star of Africa]]\n[[Category:People from Atlanta]]\n[[Category:People from Englewood, New Jersey]]\n[[Category:People from Institute, West Virginia]]\n[[Category:People from Milledgeville, Georgia]]\n[[Category:People from Washington, D.C.]]\n[[Category:Presidents of West Virginia State University]]\n[[Category:UNESCO officials]]\n[[Category:United States Department of State officials]]\n[[Category:United States National Science Foundation officials]]\n[[Category:University of Chicago alumni]]\n[[Category:YMCA leaders]]\n", "name_user": "West Virginian", "label": "safe", "comment": "Reorganization", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/John_Warren_Davis_(college_president)"}
{"title_page": "Barquero", "text_new": "{{short description|1970 film by Gordon Douglas}}\n{{Unreferenced|date=April 2019}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2015}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name     = Barquero\n| image    = Barquero poster.jpg\n| caption  = Film poster\n| director = [[Gordon Douglas (director)|Gordon Douglas]]\n| producer =\n| writer   = [[George Schenck]] <br> William Marks\n| starring = [[Lee Van Cleef]] <br> [[Warren Oates]] <br> [[Forrest Tucker]]\n| cinematography = [[Jerry Finnerman]]\n| editing = [[Charles Nelson (editor)|Charles Nelson]]\n| music = [[Dominic Frontiere]]\n| distributor = [[United Artists]]\n| country = United States\n| language = English\n| runtime = 115 minutes\n| released = {{Film date|1970|9|3}}\n}}\n\n'''''Barquero''''' is a 1970 American [[Western (genre) |Western]] film directed by [[Gordon Douglas (director)|Gordon Douglas]].\n\n\n==Plot==\nAfter stealing a shipment of silver and weapons, the brutal and unstable Remy and his band of mercenaries must cross a river in order to flee into Mexico. Travis, the maverick owner-operator of a barge that ferries people and goods across the river, learns that Remy and his band are on the way. Travis and his woman, Nola, transport the nearby settlement's inhabitants and a group of passing settlers to the river's far side. When Remy and his band arrive, Travis refuses to cross back to pick them up, knowing that Remy and his men will kill everyone else after they cross the river. A tense standoff develops between Remy and his gang, and Travis and the inhabitants and settlers, who occupy opposite sides of the river. Remy is advised by Marquette, a Frenchman he trusts. Travis is greatly assisted by Mountain Phil, a friend of his who is similarly independent-minded in the way he lives. Both Remy and Travis have to contend with dissenters within their own camps. It all explodes into a violent and bloody battle, leading to a final confrontation between the two.\n\n== Cast ==\n* [[Lee Van Cleef]] as Travis\n* [[Warren Oates]] as Remy\n* [[Forrest Tucker]] as Mountain Phil\n* [[Kerwin Mathews]] as Marquette\n* [[Mariette Hartley]] as Anna\n* Marie Gomez as Nola\n* [[Armando Silvestre]] as Sawyer\n\n== External links ==\n*{{IMDb title|065451}}\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of American films of 1970]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Gordon Douglas}}\n\n[[Category:1970 films]]\n[[Category:1970s Western (genre) films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American Western (genre) films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Gordon Douglas]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Dominic Frontiere]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Arizona]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Colorado]]\n[[Category:United Artists films]]\n\n{{1970s-Western-film-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|1970 film by Gordon Douglas}}\n{{more citations needed|date=April 2019}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2015}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name     = Barquero\n| image    = Barquero poster.jpg\n| caption  = Film poster\n| director = [[Gordon Douglas (director)|Gordon Douglas]]\n| producer =\n| writer   = [[George Schenck]] <br> William Marks\n| starring = [[Lee Van Cleef]] <br> [[Warren Oates]] <br> [[Forrest Tucker]]\n| cinematography = [[Jerry Finnerman]]\n| editing = [[Charles Nelson (editor)|Charles Nelson]]\n| music = [[Dominic Frontiere]]\n| distributor = [[United Artists]]\n| country = United States\n| language = English\n| runtime = 115 minutes\n| released = {{Film date|1970|9|3}}\n}}\n\n'''''Barquero''''' is a 1970 American [[Western (genre) |Western]] film directed by [[Gordon Douglas (director)|Gordon Douglas]].\n\n\n==Plot==\nAfter stealing a shipment of silver and weapons, the brutal and unstable Remy and his band of mercenaries must cross a river in order to flee into Mexico. Travis, the maverick owner-operator of a barge that ferries people and goods across the river, learns that Remy and his band are on the way. Travis and his woman, Nola, transport the nearby settlement's inhabitants and a group of passing settlers to the river's far side. When Remy and his band arrive, Travis refuses to cross back to pick them up, knowing that Remy and his men will kill everyone else after they cross the river. A tense standoff develops between Remy and his gang, and Travis and the inhabitants and settlers, who occupy opposite sides of the river. Remy is advised by Marquette, a Frenchman he trusts. Travis is greatly assisted by Mountain Phil, a friend of his who is similarly independent-minded in the way he lives. Both Remy and Travis have to contend with dissenters within their own camps. It all explodes into a violent and bloody battle, leading to a final confrontation between the two.\n\n== Cast ==\n* [[Lee Van Cleef]] as Travis\n* [[Warren Oates]] as Remy\n* [[Forrest Tucker]] as Mountain Phil\n* [[Kerwin Mathews]] as Marquette\n* [[Mariette Hartley]] as Anna\n* Marie Gomez as Nola\n* [[Armando Silvestre]] as Sawyer\n\n== External links ==\n*{{IMDb title|065451}}\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of American films of 1970]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Gordon Douglas}}\n\n[[Category:1970 films]]\n[[Category:1970s Western (genre) films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American Western (genre) films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Gordon Douglas]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Dominic Frontiere]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Arizona]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Colorado]]\n[[Category:United Artists films]]\n\n{{1970s-Western-film-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Bovineboy2008", "label": "safe", "comment": "fix tag", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Barquero"}
{"title_page": "Pioneer DJ", "text_new": "{{Primary sources|article|date=January 2014}}\n\n{{Infobox company\n| name = Traktor is better then pioneer no cap!\n| logo = Pioneer DJ Logo.png\n| logo_size = 220px\n| type = [[Privately held company|Privately Held Corporation]]\n| key_people = {{Plainlist|\n* Yoshiaki Ide (Chairman)\n* Akio Moriwaki (CEO)\n}}\n| industry = Hardware and software for DJ's and music production/performance\n| products = Mixer,<ref>[http://www.pioneerdj.com/en/product/mixer/ Mixer]</ref> \n\t\t\t\tPlayer,<ref>[http://www.pioneerdj.com/en/product/player/ Player]</ref> \n\t\t\t\tController,<ref name=\"controller\">[http://www.pioneerdj.com/en/product/controller/ Controller]</ref>\n\t\t\t\tAll-in-one system,<ref>[http://www.pioneerdj.com/en/product/all-in-one-system/ All-in-one system]</ref>\n\t\t\t\tTurntable,<ref>[http://www.pioneerdj.com/en/product/turntable/ Turntable]</ref>\n\t\t\t\tRemix station,<ref>[http://www.pioneerdj.com/en/product/remix-station/ Remix station]</ref>\n\t\t\t\trekordbox is gay btw <ref> [http://www.pioneerdj.com/en/product/software/ rekordbox]</ref>\n| num_employees = 253\n| foundation = [[Kawasaki, Kanagawa|Kawasaki]] ({{Start date|2014}})\n| location = [[Yokohama, Japan]]\n| owners = [[Pioneer Corporation]] <br> [[Kohlberg Kravis Roberts|KKR]] (85.05%)\n| homepage = {{URL|http://www.pioneerdj.com/}}\n}}\n\n[[File:Filtz Studio Pioneer CDJ-2000 1.JPG|thumb|The CDJ-2000, a CD player designed by Pioneer DJ. A DJM-800 mixer is also seen in the middle.]]\n'''Pioneer DJ''' (formerly Pioneer Pro DJ) is a brand of [[Pioneer Corporation]] that represents the company's range of [[DJ]] products. In March 2015 [[Kohlberg Kravis Roberts|KKR]] acquired an 85.05 percent stake.<ref>[https://www.pehub.com/2015/03/kkr-closes-buy-of-pioneer-dj/ KKR closes buy of Pioneer DJ]</ref> The Pioneer<ref>[http://pioneer.jp/corp/profile-e/ Pioneer]</ref> DJ product range comprises [[DJ mixer]]s, [[CDJ|decks]], [[headphones]], [[effects units]], all-in-one consoles,<ref name=\"all-in-one consoles\">[http://pioneerdj.com/english/products/djsystem/ All-in-one consoles]</ref> [[DJ digital controller|DJ software controllers]], [[Studio monitor|monitor speakers]] and various accessories.<ref>[http://pioneerdj.com/english/products/accessories/ DJ accessories]</ref>\nThe current professional grade [[CDJ]]-2000 Nexus 2<ref name=\"CDJ-2000nexus\">[http://pioneerdj.com/english/products/player/cdj-2000nxs.html CDJ-2000nexus]</ref> decks and [[DJM]]-900 Nexus 2<ref name=\"DJM-900nexus\">[http://pioneerdj.com/english/products/mixer/djm-900nxs.html DJM-900nexus]</ref> mixer can be seen in DJ booths all over the world.{{Citation needed|date=January 2014}}\n\n== Mixers ==\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+ Pioneer Mixers\n|-\n! Name\n! Channels\n! Years\n|-\n| DJ Gerald omuzibu\n| 2\n|-\n| DJM-300\n| 2\n|-\n| DJM-300S\n| 2\n|-\n| DJM-350\n| 2\n|-\n| DJM-400\n| 2\n|-\n| DJM-400 LIMITED\n| 2\n|-\n| DJM-450\n| 2\n| 2017 - present\n|-\n| DJM-500\n| 4\n|-\n| DJM-600\n| 4\n|-\n| DJM-700\n| 4\n|-\n| DJM-707\n| 2\n|-\n| DJM-750\n| 4\n|-\n|DJM-750MK2\n|4\n| 2017 - present\n|-\n| DJM-800\n| 4\n|-\n| DJM-850\n| 4\n|-\n| DJM-900NEXUS LIMITED\n| 4\n|-\n| DJM-900NXS\n| 4\n| 2011 - 2016\n|-\n| DJM-900NXS2\n| 4\n| 2016 - present\n|-\n| DJM-900SRT\n| 4\n|-\n| DJM-909\n| 2\n|-\n| DJM-1000\n| 6\n|-\n| SVM-1000\n| 4\n|-\n| DJM-2000\n| 4\n|-\n| DJM-2000NXS\n| 4\n|-\n| DJM-TOUR1\n| 4\n|-\n| DJM-3000\n| 4\n|-\n| DJM-5000\n| 4\n|-\n| DJM-T1\n| 2\n|-\n| DJM-S3\n| 2\n|-\n| DJM-S9\n| 2\n| 2015 - present\n|-\n| DJM-S9-N\n| 2\n|-\n| DJM-V10\n| 6\n| 2020 - present\n|}<ref>[http://www.pioneerelectronics.com/PUSA/DJ/ch.Mixers.Archived MIXERS Archived]</ref><ref>[http://www.pioneerelectronics.com/PUSA/DJ/ch.Mixers.Support MIXERS]</ref><ref>[https://www.pioneerdj.com/en/product/mixer/ DJ Mixer]</ref>\n\n== History ==\n\n*November 2001: Pioneer's first Pro DJ rack mount mixer, the DJM-3000.<ref>[http://www.pioneerdj.com/en/product/mixer/archive/djm-3000/black/overview/ Pioneer's first Pro DJ rack mount mixer]</ref>\n*November 2003: Pioneer DJ announces the DVJ-X1<ref>[http://www.pioneerdj.com/en/product/player/archive/dvj-x1/black/overview/ DJ or VJ? The Revolutionary DVJ-X1 shows the New Way]</ref> combining DJing and audio-visual entertainment.\n*October 2004: Pioneer DJ introduces two new effects processors, the EFX-1000<ref>[http://www.pioneerdj.com/en/product/remix-station/archive/efx-1000/black/overview/ EFX-1000]</ref> and the EFX-500.<ref>[http://www.pioneerdj.com/en/product/remix-station/archive/efx-500/ EFX-500]</ref>\n*2007: Pioneer DJ launches DJM-700.<ref>[https://www.bonedo.de/artikel/einzelansicht/die-10-wichtigsten-dj-mixer-der-geschichte.html Die 10 wichtigsten DJ-Mixer der Geschichte]</ref>\n*September 2009: Pioneer DJ announces two new players to their DJ equipment portfolio, the CDJ-900<ref>[http://www.pioneerdj.com/en/product/player/archive/cdj-900/black/overview/ CDJ-900: new multi-format performance DJ player.]</ref> and CDJ-2000.<ref>[http://www.pioneerdj.com/en/product/player/archive/cdj-2000/black/overview/ It\u2019s here! The CDJ-2000 pro-grade DJ player for the digital age]</ref>\n*May 2010: Pioneer DJ  releases two new DJ software controllers,<ref name=\"controller\" /> the DDJ-S1, and the DDJ-T1.\n*February 2011: Pioneer DJ announces the DJM-900nexus<ref>[http://www.pioneerdj.com/en/product/mixer/djm-900nxs/ DJM-900nexus pro DJ digital mixer: the catalyst for creativity and control]</ref> pro DJ digital mixer.\n*October 2011: Pioneer DJ officially released a new 2-channel DJ controller called the DDJ-ERGO<ref>[http://www.pioneerdj.com/en/product/controller/archive/ddj-ergo/ Introducing a new compact controller with form, the DigitalDJ-ERGO-V]</ref> at the BPM Show 2011.\n*March 2012: Pioneer DJ sets a new benchmark with the awe-inspiring RMX-1000<ref>[http://www.pioneerdj.com/en/product/remix-station/rmx-1000/black/overview/ Pioneer sets a new benchmark with the awe-inspiring RMX-1000 remix station]</ref> remix station.\n*August 2012: Pioneer DJ officially launches the XDJ-AERO,<ref>[http://www.pioneerdj.com/en/product/all-in-one-system/xdj-aero/Pioneer presents the XDJ-AERO, the first-ever wireless all-in-one DJ system, and the first native player for rekordbox\u2122 music management software]</ref> Pioneer's first wireless DJ system that plays music from smartphones and tablets via Wi-Fi.\n*August 2012: Pioneer\u2019s rekordbox\u2122 software goes mobile.<ref>[http://www.rekordbox.com Pioneer\u2019s rekordbox\u2122 software goes mobile]</ref>\n*August 2012: Pioneer DJ introduces the DDJ-WeGO,<ref>[http://www.pioneerdj.com/en/product/controller/archive/ddj-wego/ The all-new DigitalDJ-WeGO \u2013 the fun and affordable DJ console for beginners]</ref> an affordable DJ console for beginners.\n*October 2012: Pioneer DJ launches the DDJ-SX \u2013 the first native controller for Serato DJ.<ref>[http://www.pioneerdj.com/en/product/controller/ddj-sx/ Pioneer DJ launches the DDJ-SX \u2013 the first native controller for Serato DJ]</ref>\n*January 2013: Pioneer DJ unveils the limited \"Platinum Collection\" of its CDJ-2000NXS,<ref>[http://www.pioneerdj.com/en/product/player/cdj-2000nxs/platinum/overview/ CDJ-2000NXS-M - Limited Edition Platinum]</ref> DJM-900NXS<ref>[http://www.pioneerdj.com/en/product/mixer/djm-900nxs/platinum/overview/ DJM-900NXS-M - Limited Edition Platinum]</ref> and RMX-1000.<ref>[http://www.pioneerdj.com/en/product/remix-station/rmx-1000/platinum/overview/ RMX-1000-M - Limited Edition Platinum]</ref>\n*April 2013: Pioneer DJ officially launches the DJM-750.<ref>[http://www.pioneerdj.com/en/product/mixer/djm-750/ Pioneer launches the DJM-750 four-channel mixer]</ref>\n*May 2013: Pioneer DJ releases the XDJ-R1 all-in-one DJ system - the portable, rekordbox ready DJ unit that delivers wireless control from iPhone, iPad and iPod touch.<ref>[http://www.pioneerdj.com/en/product/all-in-one-system/xdj-r1/ The XDJ-R1 all-in-one DJ system \u2013 the portable, rekordbox ready DJ unit that delivers wireless control from iPhone, iPad and iPod touch]</ref>\n*August 2013: Pioneer DJ launches the S-DJ X series of active monitor speakers for DJs.<ref>[http://www.pioneerdj.com/en/product/monitor-speakers/s-dj80x/ Pioneer DJ launches the S-DJ X series of active monitor speakers for DJs]</ref>\n*June 2014: Pioneer DJ release DDJ-SX2 for fast scratching and simple cueing by its buttons.\n*July 2014: Pioneer DJ marks 20 years in the DJ industry by launching of a new turntable: the PLX-1000 <ref>[https://www.pioneerdj.com/en/news/2014/plx-1000/ PLX-1000 Turntable]</ref> aimed at the professional DJ. The PLX-1000 is designed for the DJ booth and the demands of the DJ, it also reflects 50 years experience of making turntables for the hi-fi world. The launch of a turntable in an increasingly more digital DJ environment is seen by many Djs as a response to the growing resurgence of vinyl in the youth markets with so called \"hipsters\" leading this trend. A more affordable version is also expected at this stage. The DJ level deck is also aimed at increasing number of turntablists using control vinyl  with software such as Serato. \n*August 2014: Pioneer DJ releases DDJ-WeGO3 For Algoriddim for mac IOS pc and iPad & iPad air\n*August 2015: Pioneer DJ Releases a new Mixer: The DJM-S9, a Serato capable DVS mixer with new MAGVELPRO Faders.\n*January 2016: Pioneer DJ Releases a new Nexus 2 Mixer and Player: new CDJ-2000NXS2 and DJM-900NXS2 flagship set-up <ref>[http://www.pioneerdj.com/en-us/news/2016/meet-the-new-cdj-2000nxs2-and-djm-900nxs2/ Refined, Remastered, Reborn: Meet the new CDJ-2000NXS2 and DJM-900NXS2]</ref>\n*April 2016: Pioneer DJ announces the DDJ-RB and the DDJ-RR controller. \n*May\u2013June 2016: Pioneer DJ releases 2 new MIDI-controllers: the DDJ-RB and the DDJ-RR controller.<ref>http://djtechtools.com/2016/04/26/pioneer-introduce-ddj-rb-ddj-rr-smaller-rekordbox-controllers/</ref>\n*January 2017: Pioneer DJ launches the Toraiz AS1 <ref>[https://www.pioneerdj.com/en/news/2017/toraiz-as-1-monophonic-analog-synthesizer/  Toraiz AS1]</ref> an analogue monophonic synthesiser in association with legendary electronic instrument maker Dave Smith instruments. Dave Smith has created instruments used by some of the most influential musicians of our era from Peter Gabriel (Genesis) to Trent Reznor (Nine Inch Nails), Faith No More to Lady Gaga,<ref>https://www.davesmithinstruments.com/artists/</ref> so expectations of the Toraiz AS1 are exceptionally high. Demonstrations in the UK presented by Pioneer Dj's Rob Anderson from March through to May 2017 prove that the instrument delivers that trademark analogue sound indicative of Dave Smith instruments combined with a clear user interface and high build quality which typifies Pioneer DJ products. Despite this there is still a steep learning curve to master this machine. The AS1 also has teething issues with the software when powering on. In March 2017 Pioneer release a software update aimed at solving this issue.<ref>https://www.pioneerdj.com/en/news/2017/toraiz-as-1-firmware-update-ver1021/</ref>\n*January 2020: Pioneer DJ launches the DJM-V10 6-channel professional DJ Mixer.\n\n== Headphones ==\n* [[HDJ-1000]]\n\n== References ==\n\n<!--- See [[Wikipedia:Footnotes]] on how to create references using tags which will then appear here automatically -->\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*[http://pioneerdj.com/ Pioneer DJ]\n*[http://pioneer.jp/index-e.html Pioneer Corporation (Japan)]\n\n[[Category:DJ equipment]]\n[[Category:Brands]]\n[[Category:Pioneer Corporation]]\n[[Category:Consumer electronics brands]]\n", "text_old": "{{Primary sources|article|date=January 2014}}\n\n{{Infobox company\n| name = Pioneer DJ\n| logo = Pioneer DJ Logo.png\n| logo_size = 220px\n| type = [[Privately held company|Privately Held Corporation]]\n| key_people = {{Plainlist|\n* Yoshiaki Ide (Chairman)\n* Akio Moriwaki (CEO)\n}}\n| industry = Hardware and software 